### Overview

# In this exercise, we’ll investigate cell coverage gaps using two techniques, one that uses a
# discrete model and one that is continuous. First, we’ll create buffers around cell towers in one
# county at three different radii representing different levels of network strength. For each level,
# we’ll compute the percentage of the county that is covered. Next, we’ll create a distance surface
# showing the distance to the nearest cell tower. In the process, we’ll get to practice using
# functions from the rgeos and raster packages.

### Setup

### Extract Features for One County

# 4. Select one county (e.g., San Diego) and save the boundary as a separate object. Plot it and overlay
#     the cell towers.

Find the column in the attribute table that has the name of the county.

idx <- which( ca_counties@data$CountyNAME == "San Diego County"  )
sandiego_alb <- ca_counties[idx,]
plot(sandiego_alb, asp=1)
plot(celltwrSP_alb, add=TRUE, col="red")

# 5. Using a spatial overlay, identify the cell towers which fall in your county. Save them as a
#     separate SpatialPolygons object.
  • The over() function is a multi-purpose spatial overlay function. It can return a number of different objects depending on the data type of the first two argument. You must look at the help page to figure it out.
  • over() requires all Spatial objects passed to it to be in the same CRS (projection system).
  • If needed, the geometry() function can be used to get rid of a spatial object’s data frame (e.g., convert a SpatialPolygonsDataFrame object to a SpatialPolygons object.).
sandiego_alb@proj4string <- celltwrSP_alb@proj4string
tower_in_sd_yn <- over(celltwrSP_alb, geometry(sandiego_alb))
sdtowers <- celltwrSP_alb[which(tower_in_sd_yn==1), ]
plot(sandiego_alb, asp=1)
plot(celltwrSP_alb, add=TRUE, col="red")
plot(sdtowers, add=TRUE, pch=16, cex=0.5, col="blue")

### Buffer Towers and Compute Percent Intersection

# 6. Create a one-mile buffer around each cell tower to represent the area that can receive a strong
#     signal (although not really, this is just an example). Merge them together if needed to get a
#     single polygon representing strong signal coverage.

One mile is 1609 meters.
The rgeos package has many geoprocessing functions.

library(rgeos, quietly = TRUE)
sdtowers_buff01mi <- gBuffer(sdtowers, width=1609, byid=F)
plot(sandiego_alb, asp=1)
plot(sdtowers_buff01mi, add=TRUE, col="orange")

Note we set byid=FALSE so that R will create a single merged buffer for all of the tower locations.

# 7. Next, find the proportion of San Diego County (by area) that lies within 1 mile of a cell tower.

There’s a function in the rgeos package that returns the area of features in a SpatialPolygons object.

#Area of the county:
gArea(sandiego_alb)
## [1] 11032256666
#Area of the cell tower buffers:
gArea(sdtowers_buff01mi)
## [1] 791126700
#Proportion of county
round(gArea(sdtowers_buff01mi) / gArea(sandiego_alb), 3)
## [1] 0.072

### Repeat with Larger Buffers

# 8. Repeat the previous two steps for buffer distances 5 mi and 10 mi. Plot the buffered area on top of
#     the county boundary for a reality-check.

Make sure you clip the buffered area to the county boundary to avoid over estimating the area

sdtowers_buff5mi <- gBuffer(sdtowers, width=1609*5, byid=F)
sdtowers_buff5mi_clipped <- gIntersection(sdtowers_buff5mi, sandiego_alb) 
prop5mi <- round(gArea(sdtowers_buff5mi_clipped) / gArea(sandiego_alb), 3)
plot(sandiego_alb, asp=1, main=paste("Proportion within 5 miles: ", prop5mi))
plot(sdtowers_buff5mi_clipped, add=TRUE, col="violet")
plot(sandiego_alb, add=TRUE)

sdtowers_buff10mi <- gBuffer(sdtowers, width=1609*10, byid=F)
sdtowers_buff10mi_clipped <- gIntersection(sdtowers_buff10mi, sandiego_alb) 
prop10mi <- round(gArea(sdtowers_buff10mi_clipped) / gArea(sandiego_alb), 3)
plot(sandiego_alb, asp=1, main=paste("Proportion within 10 mile: ", prop10mi))
plot(sdtowers_buff10mi_clipped, add=TRUE, col="cyan")
plot(sandiego_alb, add=TRUE)

### Create a Distance Surface

# A distance surface is a raster layer where the value of each pixel is the distance to the
# nearest cell tower. The raster package has a strong set of functions for working with raster
# data.

# The first step in this analysis is to create a raster surface that covers the extent of the
# county. We don’t need to assign values to the pixels just yet, but we need to make sure the extent
# covers the county completely, and the resolution is sufficiently fine for our desired level of
# precision.

# 9. Create a raster the covers your county. Make the spatial resolution 1/4 mile.

  • The raster() is a multi-purpose function for creating rasters either from scratch or by importing a file from disk.
  • To define a raster, you need to know at least two of the following three parameters (the third one can always be computed from the other two)
    • the extent (i.e., x and y coordinates of the corners)
    • number of rows and colums
    • resolution (pixel size)
  • Read the help page for raster() and look for an option that allows you to create a raster based on the extent of another Spatial object.
library(raster, quietly=TRUE)
quarter_mi <- 1609 / 4  ## quarter mile in meters
sd_rast <- raster(sandiego_alb, resolution=c(quarter_mi,quarter_mi))
sd_rast
## class       : RasterLayer 
## dimensions  : 266, 354, 94164  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution  : 402.25, 402.25  (x, y)
## extent      : 223778.4, 366174.9, -604647.9, -497649.4  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : +init=epsg:3310 +proj=aea +lat_1=34 +lat_2=40.5 +lat_0=0 +lon_0=-120 +x_0=0 +y_0=-4000000 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs +ellps=GRS80 +towgs84=0,0,0

# 10. Rasterize the tower locations in your county.

  • Rasterize means convert from a vector format to a raster format. You can rasterize any kind of vector feature - points, lines, or polygons.
  • When you rasterize vector features, you need to decide what the values of the cells where the vector object lies should be.
sdtowers_rast <- rasterize(sdtowers, sd_rast, field=1)
table(getValues(sdtowers_rast))
## 
##   1 
## 118

# 11. Create the distance surface and plot it.

Use the distance() function

sdtowers_dist <- distance(sdtowers_rast)
plot(sdtowers_dist)
plot(sandiego_alb, add=T, lwd=2)

Note the raster package also has a function distanceFromPoints(), which combines the rasterize and distance calculations in one step.

# 12. Save the objects you created in this exercise to disk.

save(list=c("ca_counties", "celltwrSP_alb", "sandiego_alb", "sd_rast", "sdtowers", "sdtowers_buff10mi_clipped", "sdtowers_buff01mi", "sdtowers_buff5mi_clipped" , "sdtowers_dist", "sdtowers_rast"), file="exercise3a_outputs.RData")

### Bonus Questions

# 13. Using the distance raster created above, compute the average distance to a cell tower for the
#     entire county.

  • The distance surface needs to be masked to the county boundary so you only count pixels within the county.
  • Look at the getValues() function.

First we have to clip our distance surface to the county boundary. We can do this with the mask() function from the raster package.

sdtowers_dist_clipped <- mask(sdtowers_dist, sandiego_alb)
plot(sdtowers_dist_clipped)

The pixel values are the distance to the nearest cell tower in meters. So all we need to do is grab their values and compute the mean. Fortunately the mean() function has an argument to ignore NA values.

mean(getValues(sdtowers_dist_clipped), na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 9649.171

# 14. Using buffers, compute the proportion of every county in California that lies within 5 mile of
#     a cell tower. Present these in a table ordered by the proportion.

Use a loop.

## Create an empty numeric vector to save the results
county_prp <- numeric()

## Loop through the counties SPDF
for (i in 1:nrow(ca_counties)) {
  
  ## Grab the current county boundary
  county_boundary <- ca_counties[i, ]
  
  ## Copy the projection of the cell towers to this county boundary so the overlay function works
  ## (we know they are both CA Albers, but the over() function require them to match exactly)
  county_boundary@proj4string <- celltwrSP_alb@proj4string
  
  ## Use the over() function to find out which cell towers fall within this count
  ## Note our use of the geometry() functino to turn the SpatialPolygonsDataFrame
  ## object into a SpatialPolygons object
  tower_in_cnty <- over(celltwrSP_alb, geometry(county_boundary))
  towers_sp <- celltwrSP_alb[which(tower_in_cnty==1), ]
  
  ## Create a five-mile buffer of all the towers, and clip it to the county boundary
  towers_buff5mi <- gBuffer(towers_sp, width=1609*5, byid=F)
  towers_buff5mi_clipped <- gIntersection(towers_buff5mi, county_boundary) 
  
  ## Compute the proportion of the county area that lies within a 5 mile radius of a tower
  prop5mi <- round(gArea(towers_buff5mi_clipped) / gArea(county_boundary), 3)

  ## Add the proportion to the end of the county_prp vector
  county_prp <- c(county_prp, prop5mi)
  
  ## Print a message to the console so the user knows things are working
  cat(as.character(ca_counties@data[i, "CountyNAME"]), prop5mi, "\n")
  
  ## Plotting is another way you can tell your code is working
  #plot(county_boundary, asp=1)
  #plot(towers_buff5mi_clipped, add=TRUE, col="cyan")
  #plot(towers_sp, add=TRUE, col="red")
}
